Here's a recommended structure:

**1. Make HTTP calls injectable**

```csharp
// In your MCP server project
public class WeatherTool
{
    private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;

    public WeatherTool(HttpClient httpClient)
    {
        _httpClient = httpClient;
    }

    public async Task<string> GetWeatherAsync(string city)
    {
        var response = await _httpClient.GetAsync($"https://api.example.com/weather?city={city}");
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
    }
}
```

**2. Create the test project**

```bash
dotnet new xunit -n MyMcpServer.Tests
cd MyMcpServer.Tests
dotnet add reference ../MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj
dotnet add package RichardSzalay.MockHttp   # popular mock for HttpClient
```

**3. Write tests with a mock HTTP handler**

```csharp
using RichardSzalay.MockHttp;

public class WeatherToolTests
{
    [Fact]
    public async Task GetWeather_ReturnsExpectedResult()
    {
        // Arrange — fake the external API
        var mockHttp = new MockHttpMessageHandler();
        mockHttp
            .When("https://api.example.com/weather?city=Seattle")
            .Respond("application/json", """{"temp": 62, "condition": "cloudy"}""");

        var httpClient = mockHttp.ToHttpClient();
        var tool = new WeatherTool(httpClient);

        // Act
        var result = await tool.GetWeatherAsync("Seattle");

        // Assert
        Assert.Contains("cloudy", result);
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task GetWeather_ApiError_ThrowsException()
    {
        var mockHttp = new MockHttpMessageHandler();
        mockHttp
            .When("https://api.example.com/*")
            .Respond(System.Net.HttpStatusCode.InternalServerError);

        var httpClient = mockHttp.ToHttpClient();
        var tool = new WeatherTool(httpClient);

        await Assert.ThrowsAsync<HttpRequestException>(
            () => tool.GetWeatherAsync("Seattle"));
    }
}
```

**Key principles:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **Inject `HttpClient`** | Accept it via constructor so tests can substitute a mock |
| **Mock at the handler level** | Use `MockHttpMessageHandler` (or a custom `DelegatingHandler`) — avoids wrapping `HttpClient` in an interface |
| **Test tool logic, not HTTP** | Verify your parsing, error handling, and return values |
| **Project layout** | Keep `MyMcpServer.Tests/` alongside `MyMcpServer/` in the same solution |

If you prefer no third-party mock library, you can write a minimal handler yourself:

```csharp
public class FakeHandler : HttpMessageHandler
{
    private readonly HttpResponseMessage _response;
    public FakeHandler(HttpResponseMessage response) => _response = response;

    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken ct) =>
        Task.FromResult(_response);
}
```

This pattern works for any MCP tool — the important part is **constructor-injecting `HttpClient`** so you can intercept requests at the message-handler level.
